07119nam a22010575i 9783110702286DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020944501  a97831107022867 a10.1515/97831107022862doi  a(DE-B1597)549607  a(OCoLC)1232281846  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPHI0380002bisacsh00aContext Dependence in Language, Action, and Cognition /ced. by Tadeusz Ciecierski, Paweł Grabarczyk. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VI, 252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEpistemic Studies : Philosophy of Science, Cognition and Mind ,x2512-5168 ;v4600tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tMoorean Paradoxes, Assertion, and Certainty -- tMeaning Holism and Contextualism[s]: Friends or Foes? -- tOn the Nature of Non-Doxastic Disagreement about Taste -- tWhy the Basic Problem Is Not a Problem -- tGettier Cases, Warranted Assertability Maneuvers, and the Fourth Condition -- tSelf vs Other? Social Cognition, Extended Minds, and Self-Rule -- tArticulating Context-Dependence: Ad Hoc Cognition in the Prototype Theory of Concepts -- tSuccess and Knowledge in Action: Saving Anscombe’s Account of Intentionality -- tDe Re Explanation of Action in Context, the Problem of ‘Near-Contraries’ and Belief Fragmentation -- tThe Role of Presuppositions and Default Implicatures in Framing Effects -- tTranscending the Situation: On the Context-dependence of Practice-based Cognition -- tIndirect Relations and Frames: Coreference in Context -- tAuthor‘s Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe phenomenon of context dependence is so multifaceted that it is tempting to classify it as hetergenous. It is especially evident in the case of the difference between context dependence as understood in the philosophy of language and context dependence as understood in the philosophy of mind. One of the aims of the present volume is to show that as varied as the phenomenon of context dependence is, the similarities between its different manifestations are profound and undeniable. More importantly, as evidenced in a number of papers presented on the subsequent pages of this volume, a broad perspective on the phenomenon of context dependence helps us to re-apply theories devised for one of the subfields of philosophy to the other subfields. Since the connections and analogies between many uses of contextualism may not be initially obvious, keeping an open perspective and the willingness to learn from the work of others may sometimes be crucial for finding new, satisfactory solutions.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aGeistesphilosophie. 4aPragmatik. 4aSprachphilosophie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Language.2bisacsh  aPragmatics.  alinguistic philosophy.  aphilosophy of language.  aphilosophy of mind.1 aCaamaño-Alegre, María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiecierski, Tadeusz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiecierski, Tadeusz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrawford, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGahrn-Andersen, Rasmus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrabarczyk, Paweł, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrabarczyk, Paweł, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHernández-Conde, José V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawczyński, Filip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlimczyk, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb